Rio Grande do Sul State League 2000

Copa Sport Club Rio Grande - Um Século de Futebol (A Century of Soccer)
  
Participants 
  
Clube 15 DE NOVEMBRO (Campo Bom)
Esporte Clube AVENIDA (Santa Cruz do Sul)
Sociedade Esportiva e Recreativa CAXIAS do Sul (Caxias do Sul)
Clube ESPORTIVO Bento Gonçalves (Bento Gonçalves)
GRÊMIO Football Porto Alegrense (Porto Alegre)
Esporte Clube GUARANI (Venâncio Aires)
Esporte Clube INTERNACIONAL - SM (Santa Maria)
Sport Club INTERNACIONAL (Porto Alegre)
Esporte Clube JUVENTUDE (Caxias do Sul)
Esporte Clube PASSO FUNDO (Passo Fundo)
Esporte Clube PELOTAS (Pelotas)
Sport Club RIO GRANDE (Rio Grande)*
Futebol Clube SANTA CRUZ (Santa Cruz do Sul)
Sociedade Esportiva e Recreativa SANTO ÂNGELO (Santo Ângelo)
Esporte Clube SÃO JOSÉ (Porto Alegre)
Esporte Clube SÃO LUIZ (Ijuí)
VERANÓPOLIS Esporte Clube Recreativo e Cultural (Veranópolis)
  
Byes to First phase
  
Grêmio (Porto Alegre)
Internacional (Porto Alegre)
Juventude (Caxias do Sul)       

Note: FGF, Rio Grande do Sul FA, in hommage to Sport Club Rio Grande (Rio
      Grande), the oldest Brazilian soccer team*, decided to promote the team 
      to the 2000 first level, since it celebrates its 100th anniversary.  
      Independently of the final position of Rio Grande in the championship,
      the team will be relegated.
   
* - Although Flamengo and Vasco da Gama have foundation dates prior to 1900,
    both started as rowing clubs, only after 1900 these two clubs decided to
    assemble a soccer team.  However, Rio Grande has had a period of inactivity 
    during its first century of existence, so the Brazilian team with the 
    largest period of soccer activity is Ponte Preta (Campinas).
  
